					<physDesc rend="visible">
						<p>Vellum and paper codex; Sephardic square script, partially punctuated, of 14th (for the main part)  and of 17th century (for the text added on blank pages in the manuscript)</p>
						<objectDesc form="codex">
							<supportDesc material="mixed">
								<extent>101 folios <dimensions unit="mm" type="leaf">
										<height>245 </height>
										<width>190/200</width>
									</dimensions>
									<dimensions type="written" unit="mm">
										<height>155/175</height>
										<width>130/150</width>
									</dimensions>
								</extent>
								<foliation>
									<p>101 folios (+ 1 unfoliated paper flyleaf at the end); folio 1 is a paper flyleaf.</p>
								</foliation>
								<collation>
									<p>13 quires: i10-1 (folios 2-10), ii6-1 (folios 11-15), iii-xii8 (folios 16-95), xiii6 (folios 96-101). </p>
									<p>No catchwords.</p>
									<p>Margins are too closely cut.</p>
								</collation>
							</supportDesc>
							<layoutDesc>
								<layout columns="1" ruledLines="10 26" writtenLines="10 26">
									<p>Uniform codex. </p>
									<p>The codex is called the Golden Haggadah because of the diapered gold-leaf background of its miniatures.
</p>
									<p>Ruling is visible. </p>
									<p>Hair-side and flesh-side of the folios are distinguishable.
</p>
									<p>Erased text (e. g. folios 81r, 83r, 86r, 86v, 87r, 90v, 94v, 95r, 97r). </p>
									<p>Many illustrations, which consist mainly of gold, silver, and occasionally coloured letters of first and striking words, placed within coloured designs. </p>
								</layout>
							</layoutDesc>
						</objectDesc>
						<handDesc hands="2">
							<summary>Sephardic square script, partially punctuated, of 14th (for the main part) and 17th century.</summary>
							<handNote script="Hebrew" scope="sole"/>
						</handDesc>
						<additions>
							<p>Folios 3v-16r are 17th century additions.</p>
							<p>Folio 2r is a roughly illuminated title-page from the 17th century. </p>
							<p>
								<name type="person" role="bookseller">Fra Luigi da Bologna</name>: censor&apos;s signature, Bologna, February 1599 (101v); <ref target="Popper_1969" type="page"> 104</ref> and appendix § 112-117. </p>
							<p>Rabi <name type="person" role="owner">Yo᾿av Gallico</name>of Asti, duchy of Savoy: gave the manuscript as a wedding present to his &apos;learned son-in-law Eliyahu&apos;, son of Menaḥem Rava in 1602: inscribed on his added title page (folio 2r). </p>
							<p>The armorial device of the Gallico and Rava families, added at Carpi in 1602 (folio 16r ). </p>
							<p>
								<name type="person" role="censor">Camillo Jaghel</name>: censor&apos;s signature, 1613 (folio 101v); see <ref target="Popper_1969" type="number">50-56</ref>. </p>
							<p>
								<name type="person" role="censor">Renato da Modena</name>: censor&apos;s signature, 1626 (folio 101v); see <ref target="Popper_1969" type="number">132-133</ref>. </p>
							<p>
								<name type="person" role="owner">῾Azaryah Tsedeḳiyah Ḥayim Ashkenazi</name>: birth entry on 22 January 1689 (folio 1r). </p>
						</additions>
						<bindingDesc>
							<binding>
								<p>Post-1600. Brown leather Morocco binding, blind tooled, remains of clasps.</p>
							</binding>
						</bindingDesc>
